# Comparison

| Approach    | Idea                                          | Time          | Space    |
| ----------- | --------------------------------------------- | ------------- | -------- |
| Brute Force | Try every starting value and simulate         | O(answer × n) | O(1)     |
| Optimal     | Reverse process using `ceil((ans + num) / 2)` | **O(n)**      | **O(1)** |

## Key Pattern to Remember

When a process has a linear forward transition such as:

```
new = 2 * old - value
```

and you're asked for the **minimum starting value**, think **backwards**:

1. Assume the smallest valid ending value.
2. Reverse the equation.
3. Use **ceiling** if integer values are required.

This reverse-simulation pattern appears in several greedy and mathematical array problems and often converts an expensive search into a single linear pass.
